	abstract = {Computational Thinking (CT) is a key 21st-century skill that supports systematic and creative problem-solving. However, evaluation approaches that consider individual student profiles-particularly at the elementary level-remain limited. This study aims to analyze the relationship between student profiles (age, gender, grade level, and mathematics scores) and CT performance using a Game-Based Learning (GBL) approach through a 5 × 5 mazestyle board game. The instrument includes 30 questions at three difficulty levels, assessing four CT concepts and five CT skills. Data were collected from 70 students in grades 4 to 6 across two public elementary schools in Indonesia. Statistical analysis was conducted using Pearson/Spearman correlation, T-test, ANOVA, and multiple linear regression. Results indicate that mathematics scores significantly predict CT performance (p<0.001), followed by gender, while age and grade level were not significant. This study introduces a novel CT evaluation model using a physical board game that integrates student profiles to support adaptive learning design. The findings offer a foundation for developing more personalized and effective learning media in elementary education.  © 2025 IEEE.},
