	pages = {319 - 348},
	doi = {10.4018/979-8-3373-1998-8.ch011},
	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105024618254?origin=resultslist},
	abstract = {Artificial Intelligence (AI) is transforming primary school mathematics education by offering adaptive learning experiences, personalized instruction, and real-time feedback for students. AI-powered tools, automated assessment platforms, and data-driven learning analytics, enable teachers to address diverse student needs effectively. One of AI’s key contributions is adaptive learning, where algorithms analyse student performance and adjust lesson complexity accordingly. AI enhances automated assessment, reducing teacher workload by providing instant feedback and identifying learning gaps. However, successful AI integration in primary mathematics education requires teacher training and ethical considerations, including data privacy and fair AI implementation. Teachers must be equipped with the necessary digital skills to effectively utilize AI tools while maintaining a balance between technology and human-centered pedagogy. AI has the potential to revolutionize primary mathematics education, making learning more inclusive, engaging, and effective for young learners. © 2026 by IGI Global Scientific Publishing. All rights reserved.},
